Prague transport companies will also be transporting on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1st, 2008, will go down in the history of Prague's transport companies as a date when the first passengers carrying an electronic coupon in their pocket, instead of a paper ticket, will board a metro, tram or bus.
These can currently buy about one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it simultaneously played on their chip card at the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádra
Since yesterday the coupons are also available via the Internet on the websites of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use the internet sales can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they had to wait regularly in long queues for their paper tickets.
They buy the coupon via the Internet, which is played on the opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"There is also a desk with trained staff available to travellers at these points, which advises those interested in buying the Internet and also puts the coupon on the card," said the spokesperson of the Martin Opatrný project.
In addition to the libraries, electronic coupons can also be played on the opencard on self-service machines, which are installed in some underground vestibules.
What do such machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket devaluers, passengers may have noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but it should be eighty by the end of the year," Opatrný adds.
The coupon is controlled by an automatic machine instead of the driver
The operation of the machines, which will work from tomorrow, is easy.
All you have to do is insert the chip card, and the coupon you bought before will play itself.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with numbers 300 to 499, with which especially the inhabitants from municipalities of the region of Central Bohemia get into the capital.
"In the trains that form part of Prague's integrated transport system, train attendants have readers who can check the validity period of the coupons according to time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the organisation Ropid. This organisation compiles the timetables for Prague's transport companies.
The suburban buses have card readers at the driver's desk.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver, but the open card must be placed at a marked point on the side of the checkout.
The driver thus checks the validity of the coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the coupons, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information," says Drápal.
A passenger who does not use suburban buses and no longer knows when the validity of the coupon ends can go to the self-service machines, where the coupons are played on the card.
Here the information about the validity of his documents is displayed on the display of the device.
The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the US
In 1945 the Sudeten Germans had requested the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States.
This is evident from a letter which is stored in the collections of the South Bohemian scientific library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we would at least like to live under the auspices of the United States of America.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans are said to have turned to the US President in 1945.
This is evident, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and which is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian scientific library.
In the letter the Germans of Krumau ask the American President not to allow the return of the "Sudetungus" - which was taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich agreement - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units do not enter German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," says a letter signed with the words "people to whom the fate of the Sudeten lies at the heart."
Since the connection to Czechoslovakia leads the Sudeten Germans - in knowledge of the Czech national character - to suspect that they would expect brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over the protection over the Bohemian Forest for today and forever.
"We can't believe that without regard to the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants of this area, you promised a state that is foreign to us, which suppresses and tries to eliminate minorities and has contributed absolutely nothing to the victory of the Allies" is read in the letter.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly the fear of revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the US President had doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it would be sufficient if he in the Böhmerwaldgau initiated a referendum on whether the inhabitants wanted to become part of the USA or live under the protection of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naive in today's knowledge of post-war history, according to some contemporary witnesses, however, it paints a good picture of the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at that time.
Even if the Bohemian Germans at least had to suspect that they would negotiate their deportation from the Republic, only a few of them admitted such a possibility at all.
Some were waiting for the United States and Great Britain to negotiate some kind of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Others believed that they could simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
He was employed as a Budweiser German in the Baltic Sea Navy during the war.
When he came into British captivity at the end of the war and was taken to a prisoner of war camp in Holstein, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that if they came home, the Czech would fit them," said Chalupa.
None of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war expected him to be expelled from the Republic on the basis of the Beneš decrees.
