Even rats have feelings
A rat or a cockroach flees in case of danger, does that mean that she also feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
Just how could you check if they feel the same way they behave like us?
For several years, contributions by famous scientists have been published in the internet magazine Edge.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove this so far where we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we may at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and raise questions of feeling or, more generally, of consciousness, we enter rough terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat gets in danger, she does the same as many other animals: she turns herself dead, flees or attacks.
People behave similarly, which is why some scientists conclude a comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and in the execution/control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in man than in the other primates and seems to be completely lacking in other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity may lie in the linguistic nature of man: Since such a large part of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, however it may be, probably differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it is neither measured nor analysed on the basis of our own experience, because of the special hardware, then its exploration presents us with great problems.
Most of my remarks relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that should be more accessible scientifically.
One could examine the processes of consciousness of animals without regard to their contents, and that is exactly what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, one shifts rather to the neural correlates of consciousness than to the causal mechanisms: both may be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the formation of visualization.
What is the result of the sensations?
I attribute it to the fact that an emotional system such as fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies memory.
From this point of view, sensations are closely linked to the regions of the Cortex that characterize primates, especially humans.
Connected with the linguistic nature, subtle gradations of feeling arise, because with the help of words and grammar we can differentiate and categorize states in order to attribute them to others besides ourselves.
Antonio Damasio, on the other hand, believes that sensations from more primitive activities in the body-feeling regions of the Cortex and the brain-stem are similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain-stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it may well be involved in cross-genuine sensations.
In theory, I can't disagree with that, but I think it's unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in rats and humans is likely to feel the same in both cases: but how can one check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
A cockroach flees in case of danger whether it also feels fear?
In my eyes, mere behavioral similarity cannot yet prove an equal experience.
While the neural comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain strains, cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove it for humans, how did you want to prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, perhaps even cockroaches (who knows?), have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably fundamentally different from ours (since the human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore the emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
