The pride and the hardships in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden between the growth of theme parks around Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, noisy and gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet city where the pride and complications of African American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first completely black city in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Today it is a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet the city that she describes – and that made her a tourist destination by taking her to the Florida travel guide, which was produced by the federal writer project at the time of the depression – is and remains in many ways a very special place.
Eatonville is as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's missing."
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidacy, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open conversation on racial relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
"We are very concerned about how our story is told," says Hortense Jones, 59, a resident of the city from birth and a member of the congregation of the city's oldest church.
It must be true."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of almost 2,400 inhabitants, where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is on the one hand a stronghold of literature and on the other hand an example of the black culture - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and on guard.
And the concerns about Eatonville's image really started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973)
Five paragraphs in the Florida Guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the locations of black history and human drama.
Naughty as Oskar both in real life and in literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Beyond the street to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-white painted modern school, with its well-kept gardens and playgrounds that Howard Miller always takes care of, although he can hardly read and write."
She also mentioned the new husband of widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of any kind and whatever--always fits to hour rooms."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by all.
"Zora described things as they were," said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston by quoting the men who sang songs about their beauty, full of sexual allusions.
She added, "Some people didn't like this."
Hurtson is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston came to the city roaring, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and wearing trousers, in a city that even today imagines something about her venerable style of clothing.
According to Mr Franklin, most of the inhabitants were fascinated, while many despised them.
"People were always happy to see Zora," said Mr Franklin.
But "she never stayed too long," he added while rocking in his chair, on a back terrace looking at Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Together with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous writer, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville there was no great memorial, no public readings on a large scale.
"I don't think they understood their contribution in the world or their heritage in the least," says Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a biography about Hurston published in 2003.
The change came in the 1980s.
Orange County authorities wanted to put a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community's slow two-lane main street.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in his history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950 ’ s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred into the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys often came and threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting away," said Mr. Franklin.
"There was even once a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In 1955, in a letter to Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the request of the Supreme Court to force integration by calling its decision against the school council in the Brown case "infringing rather than respecting my race".
Residents today say that although the abolition of racial segregation was positive in some respects, it weakened group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its young people.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - hugging his teacher in the morning and hugging his teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri , daughter of Ella Dinkins and managing director of the non-profit group to protect the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained for so long, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"One did not embrace his white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there is a cultural gap," said Ms. Nathiri.
However, civil rights have helped create room for further Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors, and artists who overcame prejudice, as they did, with positive self-confidence and statements such as: "How can anyone deny the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, the writer Alice Walker set out for Hurston's nameless tomb and began fighting for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much-praised Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway was found on the bookshelves and made them again part of the American literary canon.
The highway project came exactly at a time when Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again in public light.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbor saw her as a savior.
The municipality began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans of a five-lane highway revived the city, speeded it up at top speed, and aroused real civil pride," said Ms. Nathiri.
Mrs. Boyd expressed it a little easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project has contributed to a change in the city's self-image.
More and more people arrived, like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to re-evaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the national historical register in 1998.
A new one-story library (of course named after Hurston) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Nowadays Eatonville is still a special feature in Florida: only 6 miles from Orlando city centre can it sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It's 90% black these days.)
Outsiders looking for the history of Eatonville and its meaning are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, permission is required in advance and certain things - such as the wall painting of Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in the field work - cannot be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Mrs. Jones, a courageous, self-confident teacher with a preference for dark red, still fear that their shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival grew, an elevated degree of home pride was born.
Young people in particular tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her whole race: beautiful, with all his problems, neither worse nor better and just as proud, creative and diligent, silly and mixed up like any other race and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or the police, who could use some help according to him.
And even the younger ones, such as Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who just pass through here will think, "Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others," said Alondra Kenon the other day on a Sunday after the church.
"But if you actually stop and look at your story for a moment, it's a very nice city."
