`Sangre de mayo': Heldenbuch von Garci
Inspired by `Episodios Nacionales' by Benito Pérez Galdós, José Luis Carci in `Sangre de mayo' represents the revised version of the famous Spanish uprising against the French. This is an admirable film in filmography, with about 15 million euros investment for filming.
In this way, the Cineast has tried to 'present a lot of personalities and social analysis', which he has always admired in the works of the famous novelist, Carci explained today in the presentation of the film with Quim Gutiérrez and Paula Echevarría at the beginning of a long list of actors.
`Sangre de mayo', with a film length of more than two and a half hours, will be presented this Friday in cinemas and later shown on Telemadrid as a four-hour miniseries.
José Luis Garci, a great fan of Galdós' literature, assures us that thanks to this filming his 'childhood dream' came true. He owes this to Esperanza Aguirre, who commissioned him three years ago from the autonomous community of Madrid to make a memorial film for the second century celebration in Madrid on 2 November. Especially because the story is based on 'Episodios Nacionales', he accepted the commission.
The total contribution of 15 million made for filming by the autonomous community of Madrid, Garci, as he added, offers the 'one-time opportunity' with the help of decorations and corresponding clothing the image of 'confused Spain, who chose the wrong leader for the struggle, because the people had been brought to a standstill by the struggle for independence and under the rule of Ferdinand VII'.
However, the Cineast regrets that the financing could not be expected as in `Alatriste' or `Los fantasmas de Goya' (twice as high as in `Sangre de mayo'), so some scenes from the script could not be shot with Horacio Valcárcel, with whom Garci worked almost all his career.
For this reason, Garci, who was also film director in `Volver a empezar', was involved in his usual way of working: he stood on stage with the actors, with whom you first have to rehearse before you start shooting and for those who did not cast, he appeared `humiliating' and giving respect, `a part of the profession of film director is to provide help in theatre and cinema to know what is happening in the cinema industry in which you work.'
Many actors he encounters in `Sangre de mayo' have to repeat in front of his camera, as in the case of Miguel Rellán, Carlos Larrañaga or Fernando Guillén Cuervo.
Garci, Oscar candidate in four nominations (of which he won one), believes that none of the three candidates who represent Spain before the Academy of Hollywood this year represents a young generation of Spanish filmography. Neither `Sangre de mayo' nor `Siete mesas de billar francés' nor, finally, the selected film `Los girasoles ciegos'.
Garci does not expect awards for this film.
'In the beginning you think you're working for the offspring, later you realize that it's just for flourishing, and now you're happy when you've produced another movie,' says Garci after more than 30 years of working.
Isabel Bayón recalls the memory of the dancer from Seville Tórtola Valencia
A flamenco dancer from Seville adores a dancer who also comes from Seville.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia: her father was Catalane (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and her mother Andalusian (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), she was born in the Triana district and when she was three years old, her family moved to London.
She was a dancer and expert for oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, she was one of the first fighters for the emancipation of women, such as Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist, vegetarian, and campaigned for the abolition of the corset, which restricted the free female movement.
Isabel Bayón was fascinated by the life of this woman, who left her mark on the dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe in the period between the wars.
'I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested this role to me, which seemed impossible to me.'
'We are not trying to tell about her life, but to preserve her Esprit,' said the flamenco dancer.
Your dance bases have helped me a lot in Flamenco.
For example, 'The Dance of the Butterfly' seemed to me like Guajira, or 'The Dance of the Snake' like Tango.
Her dancing was sensual and I was told that my dancing was also in this aesthetic area,' she claims.
The production anticipates two extraordinary collaborations: Miguel Poveda, who will sing again for Isabel at one of her performances, as he did in 'La puerto abierta'; and Flamenco master Matilde Coral, who wanted to work together with one of her ex-students.
`Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I am happy because she agreed to participate in my work, and I am very honoured.'
The production also includes musical composition and the guitarists Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, the singing of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa el Viola and the collaboration with actor Juanfra Júarez, he 'takes over the role of companion of the artists who were divas, in whom he falls in love again and again.'
This work also tells in a certain way about the life of this woman, who became known in places as far away as India, the United States or Russia, and also throughout Europe, although she usually lived in London.
"I wanted to recall her, because I think she is one of the women who have an enormous influence on a particular era and whose works no one knows about today and therefore she is even less appreciated," says Bayón.
The performance takes place today at 20:30 in the theatre Lope de Vega.
