The drivers, who can relapse because of the alcohol level, will have to install the `Alcolock'.
The authority orders that the driver, who had three official penalties for the alcohol level, installs this system in his car, which forbids him to start the car in a drunken state. If he is alcoholic, then the car does not start.
The initiative was already announced last month in June and is already part of the report of the Attorney General’s Office. According to her, this is a pilot project that will last for one year.
The purpose is to resocialise the driver, which is why he gets a course for the re-education of traffic behaviour.
In addition to the Prosecutor General's Office, as experience has shown, the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for the Safety of Automobiles will also participate.
According to statistics, between 30-75 % of drivers who were reported more than once for driving under the influence of alcohol were again driving.
The `alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air and prevents auto-start when the driver has made alcohol test; or if an alcohol concentration is determined which is higher than allowed.
It costs more than EUR 1 000, the costs are borne by the person who imposes the penalty.
In this context, a study carried out in the USA in 2007 showed that cars equipped with these devices prevent up to 65% of standard violations in the first year after its introduction.
In Spain, 115 lives are expected to be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to tackle this behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And in order to facilitate their implementation, a legislative reform can be implemented in the ordinary way, and yet a reform of the Basic Law is required, which is necessary for the prosecution process.
The device is still in the Spanish markets, in no store available, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
The House of Representatives will vote tomorrow because of the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses, which has already been done in France.
