Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice-Director-General of the Canadian Barrick Gold Gold Mine.
This confirms, and pursues an orwellian logic, that the world's largest gold mining company sought a libel lawsuit of six million against three authors and a small destitute publishing house, with the aim of opening a 'public transparent debate'.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially not in the case of libel lawsuits, but the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to hold a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to express one of their opposite opinions.
No matter how the trial ends, the authors and editors of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defenses and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid out of the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
By the way, the tactics in these unequal struggles are often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensual settlement that silences the other side and also deters anyone who dares to deal with the question again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things before public opinion.
In contrast to what is common in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates are usually held in Canada through the exchange of ideas rather than by billets.
So it would have been enough if the Gold Mine had disclosed its books and files and opened up a real debate through which newspapers, media, publications and the financing of independent audit teams could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and wipes aside the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada with a hand move.
Could Mr Garver explain how he can at the same time ask for a 'public' debate and yet disregard the opinions of this very public?
It seems that this word in the Vice-President's world includes only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a rather cramped view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public, who supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada, does so mainly because it rejects the brutal attitude of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not within a framework that many perceive as a gag complaint (in the course of the 'public debate' Barrick Gold has just addressed a demand to the authors of Noir Canada, in which it demands that they no longer use this term...).
Apart from Mr Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's complaint is a direct attack on freedom of academic research and truth-finding, which are fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to quote credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to explore and discuss issues that the rich companies of the world do not like, then who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could lead it by following the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate complaint clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she does not want a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate, and it is time for governments to take measures to limit this type of unjustified lawsuit.
Rescue for Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans get along
The Bush administration and senior congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally came to an agreement yesterday on the most comprehensive economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to stop the financial crisis, which has been shaking Wall Street for months, still needs to be adopted by the two Congressional Chambers.
The main content is: better control by MEPs of the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the public funds used, new dispositions to reduce the number of houses pledged due to arrears, and the right to monitor the salaries paid to the executives of the supported companies.
American finance secretary Henry Paulson, President of the Chamber of Deputies Nancy Pelosi, and Republican representative present at the negotiations, Senator Judd Gregg, announced yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, the good news, after a two-day negotiating marathon.
'We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be market-effective,' said the Bush administration representative, Henry Paulson.
'Everything was done to protect the real economy and the American people from the price crisis on Wall Street,' declared the Democrat.
'This is the basic point: if we do not do this, the trauma, chaos and unrest in the daily lives of the Americans will be enormous,' explained Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had accelerated over the last two hours, for fear of the effect that a renewed failure would have had on the mood of investors.
The deadline that had been agreed was the market opening this morning.
The two American presidential candidates, who took part in the negotiations late in the day, were more likely to support the agreement, but did not fail to express their dissatisfaction with the need to meet them in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barrack Obama insisted on the addition of certain dispositions to agree, especially those to allow owners to keep their homes, and those relating to the salaries of senior employees of state-saved businesses.
'If you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain persons, that is nothing to which we could congratulate ourselves.
