The psychology of overbidding - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the bargain bids.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to even pay excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was supposed to play lottery, while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were investigated by functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain cortex, was measured among losers of the auction, in which the outbidding of the opponent plays an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also carried out investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should compete against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group were also promised 15 dollars in reward, in case they emerged as winners of the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was therefore only that the emphasis on one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
However, as proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the group playing "against losing" were prepared to make higher bets than those in the control or "win" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have so far only justified the behaviour observed at auctions with the pleasure of winning or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological methods, so that we now have a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Business Faculty of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should the doctor be consulted?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the generic term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - inflammation of the liver and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E, through the digestive tract (e.g. contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as semen, vaginal secretion or saliva).
Travellers are recommended vaccination against viruses A and B, against virus C there is no vaccine.
The symptoms of hepatitis A are approximately two to three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes bright, the urine dark, and recovery can take up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die annually from hepatitis B-induced, far more severe diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in 10 people are infected with medication.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen destroys the liver cells insidiously - in many cases the first symptoms show up after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular checks, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who have undergone blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognised in good time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby preventing the risk of infection and preventing the emergence of cancer.
30 September is the World Day of Hepatitis, held for the first time in 2004 by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to increase awareness of this chronic inflammation of the liver caused by viruses, their development and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
Recent research shows that religious faith acts like a kind of "pain," which is said to have facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have carried out an interesting experiment: it was investigated to what extent faith in God influences the feeling of pain in humans, reported the British paper "Telegraph".
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the faithful were able to eliminate most of the pain.
By means of a brain scan technology, it could even be demonstrated that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain control.
The study was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university participate.
During the experiment, a sparkling device was attached to the left hand of the subjects, which gave off the electric shocks.
The participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: on the one hand a picture of the Mother of God painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other Leonardo da Vinci's "Dame with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary among the faithful would create a kind of religious trance while choosing da Vinci's image, because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt comforting.
The subjects spent half an hour each in an MRI scanner, and during this time received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages, while they were supposed to look at either the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that at the sight of the Mother of God they felt "in security," as if they were "concerned," and they felt "rest and peace."
During the viewing of the religious painting, they reported 12% less pain than if they had Leonardo's work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also took part in the experiment, said that one could also produce similar effects with other strong-acting images also with the atheists, one only had to find the corresponding photo.
"We would have to find a picture that triggers very positive sensations, such as a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change our personality, and in many cases it does," says Wright.
After these excellent results, only the question remains of what effect a Madonna painting of Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the pain regulation of the faithful.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
You are what you share about yourself
On the occasion of its tenth birthday, Google can rightly claim that it is in people's pockets just as it is above their heads in the sky: it knows where people have spent their holidays, which doctors they are going to, and what moves them.
And still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of Google's managing directors.
In the direction of skeptics plagued by Orwell's horror visions, he says: These would just overlook the essence of Web 2.0.
In an interview with the Financial Times, Schmidt recently said that Google's main goal is to collect even more personal data about users, thus getting closer to the company's original goal of "organizing all the information in the world."
Schmidt explained that after ten years of world-changing work, Google was still only at the beginning of collecting information.
Asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said: he wanted Google to be able to answer questions like "What should I do tomorrow?" or "Which job really suits me?", but software programs are not yet able to do so, as they don't know enough about the users.
Not all internet users are aware that the search terms will be registered in the course of their internet searches, as well as the IP addresses from which they were searched and the pages visited.
For example, the "Personalized Search" introduced two years ago allows visitors to save their own search history and later use it so that the hits can be generated much more precisely later, and the same logic is also based on the so-called "Recommendations" with which the system recommends tailor-made products and services based on previous preferences.
However, users wonder what happens in the event of data misuse - "If you look what I do" - some people are worried about the Google data monopoly.
In most cases, however, it is more the potential power represented by the company that is frightening, and less the feeling of guilt or fear of punishment, the pursuit of freedom or the rebellion against the power that many internet users reject.
However, it is a proven fact that the search terms are not only stored, but also passed on to third parties in the event of an incident, and in these legal cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the Internet user.
A prime example of this was recently the action against paedophilia in Brazil, during which Google provided the Brazilian government with information collected by the community site called "Orkut" and also made it possible to identify the paedophilia.
However, users concerned about personal rights could still breathe in May, when Google and the civil rights organization EFF successfully took the FBI to justice: therefore, Google cannot be forced to release information to the FBI on a secret request with any point of the Constitution in the future.
(However, the Federal Government has successfully obtained the publication of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms by reference to the Youth Protection Act adopted years ago, but the list of individual users, respectively their web and search terms list, was withheld retroactively to two months.)
So Google's image remains controversial: those who hate to release their personal data because they fear the loss of their privacy and privacy through the use of Google services, scourge the company with the outrage due to the conservative companies.
However, the American "geek culture", which is present in many countries and enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users united, sees the next generation of "cool entrepreneurs" in them, unlike Microsoft, which is the market leader thanks to Windows, even though both are struggling for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that unlike Microsoft, Google does not require any identification codes for its users and makes its services available free of charge, so that an open, constantly updated source code and program package seem to be far more attractive, youthful and cooler than the official practices of the software giant.
On the other hand, the geeks see through the problematic relationship between personal rights and the Internet razor-sharp - a relationship that has become particularly central in recent years thanks to the term "Web 2.0".
The "Web 2.0" is about nothing else but collaboration, i.e. the users deliberately leave traces and use the available communication channels, and even if the dimensions are individually different, the main thing remains the same, namely to show oneself publicly.
An average youth can manage his profile on multiple community portals at the same time - from Facebook via Xanga, can connect it to each other through other services such as Twitter, or music services such as last.fm, and can eventually integrate all of this into a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. In addition, they can run blogs that automatically display the latest photo galleries that are geostified on Flickr or Picasa.
And a number of other exemplary cases prove: When looking at last night's party photos, the girlfriend will soon find out who her unfaithful friend was having fun with, or the employee will be fired because in his blog he is all too honest about his anger about the management of the company - one thing is certain: the term "privacy" has now been completely reinterpreted.
Those who lead an online life are what they reveal - so one could formulate the basic idea behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who tries to keep something secret, or even bypass the Google Monopoly, can do so with pleasure - such as Scroogle, a tool that accesses Google's search engine, but deliberately leaves no traces.
Not a few people deliberately do not register on community sites so that they cannot be found, but Google's online applications, such as word processing and graphical tools and RSS feeds, can also be handled with alternative versions that are not linked to huge server parks and therefore do not generate the best possible profile from the user.
However, public opinion waits for Google to show its true face.
With its current value of USD 156 billion, the company is even ahead of IBM (USD 140 billion), Intel (USD 124 billion) or Coca-Cola (USD 110 billion), AdWords/AdSense's advertising space is threatening the revenues of advertising agencies, and the increasingly rapid introduction of services is causing worry not only to Microsoft but also to other software developers.
However, critical viewers also find the disturbing counter-poles: For example, the Executive Board rejected a protest by the employees completely after the fees of the company's own kindergarten were doubled, and management also thought that the multiple meals of the employees were too expensive. However, all this seems to be mild against Google even going down in 2006 before the Chinese government and agreeing to an agreement that all dissident hits, or those that violate the good taste, would be filtered out.
The internal regulation of the Group is that no new service is advertised in advance, but only when it is already available. Nevertheless, the events of the coming months and years could turn a lot around again: While some believe that Google's book and magazine scan or archiving project is now assuming that the company would soon have to deal with the Supreme Court, others are concerned about the system "Health", which allows the creation of a complete health profile based on findings, doctors and problems.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database already provides the next generation of sci-fi authors with the material - such as "Scroogled", the famous novel by Cory Doctorow describes a future in best Orwellian fashion, in which a person becomes frighteningly approachable thanks to Google-related data.
