Intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop new technologies for accident prevention, if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
Like the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented that inspired the Nissan engineers of Hummeln in creating new accident-avoiding systems.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic system controlled by car robots, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protective shield," said Kazuhhiro Doi, Product Manager for Technology PR and Research Development, at the exhibition.
The compound eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
In order to imitate the function of the assembled eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
It identifies obstacles before the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of a second, and the car robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver is purely instinctive.
"If it weren't, the car robot wouldn't be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Autorobot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are currently considered unavoidable.
The entire process must reflect the behaviour of the bees when they dodge other bees.
And this has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, the dodging can not be done up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and that only in the direction of the maneuverability of the tires.
While there are endless possibilities for the bees to avoid other bees, the researchers were only able to use rotational motion or acceleration and braking in the car robot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life span than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It doesn't have to save them, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction based on previous maneuvers, so it constantly takes up just a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could be the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately steering the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the finish line.
