There was a decline in the price of crude oil (1.4 percent), electrical and technical equipment (0.9 percent), and wood processing (0.1 percent).
Prices in paper production, publishing and printing remained unchanged.
In other branches of the manufacturing industry, price increases were measured between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the important domestic sales markets of industry, such as electricity, gas, steam and water supply, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly as a result of the gas price increase introduced on 1 July.
Looking at the domestic sales markets of the manufacturing industry year-on-year, crude oil processing prices have risen most (32.4 percent).
In the metalworking sector, a 13.2 percent increase was observed, while the increase in the production of food, beverages, and tobacco was 11 percent.
A drop in prices was observed in the textile industry (2.5 percent) and in electrical and technical equipment (0.3 percent).
The rate of inflation in the other manufacturing industries ranged from 0.6 to 9.1 percent.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry rose by 10.2 percent last year.
Prices for electricity, gas, steam and water rose by 18.7 percent year-on-year.
On the domestic market, the highest price increase was recorded in the fixed assets sector in August (0.7%).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices rose by 0.3 per cent, while in the energy and processing sectors, they remained the same as in the previous month.
The largest price increase in August 2008 was observed in the energy and re-use sectors (16.8 per cent) compared to the same period in 2007.
In consumer goods-producing sectors, prices rose by 6.8 percent, while in fixed goods, prices fell by 1.4 percent.
Industrial export prices measured in Forint rose by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, but there was a decrease of 3.9 percent year-on-year.
The domestic currency grew by 1.7 percent compared to the euro, by 7.1 percent to the dollar, and compared to the price of August 2007, it grew by 7.5 percent compared to the euro, and by 15.9 percent to the dollar.
