"The vast majority of Roma youth do not have secondary education and, thanks to poor primary education, only a small part of them can obtain a university degree".
Járóka also stressed that education was a fundamental human right, which would play a key role in asserting other human rights.
Investing in the early training of Roma children could strengthen the economy of EU member states.
In the view of the honourable Members, it is important that these connections become as broad a circle as possible, i.e. Roma and non-Roma.
The earlier a Roma pupil starts school, the more his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market increase; and by means of income and turnover taxes they contribute to national spending.
"As citizens of the Union, the right to high-quality education must be guaranteed to the Roma - poor and segregated education must be stopped" said Lívia Járóka.
