Napolitano: "Prevention against accidents at work is crucial"
Every day 2500 accidents occur in Italy, three people die and 27 remain invalids for life.
For 2007, the Inail data (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were around 1200.
These figures show the seriousness of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
Today the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) will celebrate the 58th national day for the victims of accidents at work in all the provinces of Italy in order to draw the attention of the social institutions and media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data disseminated by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm how crucial the issue of prevention in the workplace is," confirms the President of the Republic of Giorgio Napolitano in his communication to the President of the Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The head of state expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to prevention at the workplace, to the protection of injured workers, to aid the families of victims and to raising public opinion".
"An outraged "basta" has risen to this point; understandable in the case of tragedies, which, in terms of scale, trigger some vortexes in the media and public participation. However, everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events, which can even be repeated in their own dynamics."
Napolitano does not hide that "there is definitely also a resource problem: it has to be invested decisively in education and information."
The numerous initiatives for a more direct awareness in school frameworks by young people who feed on the world of work are of particular importance.
It is our duty to focus attention on this phenomenon and not to distract it from its social seriousness. We must put into effect and improve a legislative norm.
For his part, the President of the Chamber, Gianfranco Fini, stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency, which insults the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards decisive rules aimed at putting an end to the problem".
"Data from accidents at work seem to indicate a slight improvement, but this does not exclude that the number of work-related deaths is far too high," emphasises Anmil President Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this "positive tendency" to mean less attention. That's what the tragedy ultimately causes."
"We believe that one does not really do enough to counter the phenomenon of accidents. One can fight against it through various actions.
