"A further effort is needed - he added - in terms of communication and awareness of public opinion.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon that is a social emergency is required".
Mercandelli also referred to "the progressive deterioration of protection for the victims of accidents at work" and denounced the "abolition of the social system we have been fighting against in recent years".
"The aim is therefore to give the worker back a guarantee on insurance so that the fate of the victim of an accident at work does not depend on voluntary or accidental donations, which are decided from time to time by a legislator".
Mp3 player under charge: danger of hearing damage
Listening to loud music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as Mp3 players, can lead to permanent hearing damage.
This is reported by the European Commission, which, in a report published today in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Csrseri (scientific committee on the current and recently identified health risks) of the EU.
"The report states in a note that 5-10 % of those who listen to loud music with portable music devices for at least five years per week for more than one hour a day risk permanently losing their hearing."
"I am worried that such a large number of young people, who usually put portable music devices and mobile phones at a high volume, will irretrievably damage their hearing without knowing it," says Meglena Kuneva.
"The scientific findings – as the Eu states – show a clear risk that pushes for rapid action.
What really matters is to raise consumers' awareness and make this information public.
In the light of these scientific findings, we must re-examine the existing control systems so that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology."
Brussels had commissioned the independent scientific committee in view of the widespread use of portable music equipment among young people.
"The scientists - the EU communication concludes - confirm that there is a legitimate concern and that the European Commission, together with the other Eu members and stakeholders, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise coming from portable music equipment and similar equipment".
There is already a European standard, which limits the level of noise from portable music equipment to 100 dB, and concerns about the damage that could result from excessive noise exposure.
One can very much limit this damage by resorting to solutions such as reducing the volume and the length of the noise exposure.
In its report, the scientific committee of the Eu points out that if users of portable music equipment listen to loud music only five hours a week (more than 89 decibels) so that the legal limits that apply to the maximum noise level at the workplace have already been exceeded.
Those who exceed this limit are risking the complete loss of hearing within five years.
This would therefore affect 5-10% of users of such devices, the number of which can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
