The elite is in danger
The phenomenon had already been revealed a few days ago when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the $700 billion White House savings package: a large part of the Americans were and is more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's issue of the New York Times, which reports on how the crisis gradually divides the Republican party, which increasingly divides itself into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favored state institutions and business community, and those neoconservatives that are hostile to "those in Washington" and the financial world, and, above all, wins voters in the south and the center of the states.
This part of the party owes its rise mainly to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
This example just mentioned is, however, only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake announces or even already represents: not only in the US, but also throughout the West, and perhaps beyond, will be affected by it.
Both in the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to speed up the long-awaited events that are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the new discovery, the outrageous renaissance of the state in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis means a decline in banking and financial institutions, which have close links with foreign countries and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the assets of private households that live in a single state.
This is an immediate political problem for governments: how to behave towards the families concerned, which are also a huge mass of voters.
The crisis therefore appears global economically, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have been sidelined in itself and lost its right to speak: the clear proof of this has been given by the EU, which, due to its division into various national and international conflicts, cannot find a common path.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and especially distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis became more and more serious, only the US is in the economic situation to save itself without foreign aid.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use it: thus two conditions – under certain circumstances – that are not to be overrated, which otherwise no international organization and no market will be able to resort to in a similar way.
The new emphasis placed on the state-national element, moreover, is perfectly in line with the growing importance that has recently been associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is just now that we were so convinced that we have long since entered a networked empire, a realm of ever-differentiated technologies, of immateriality, that we must all at once determine how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
These can certainly all be transported from one place to the other of the world, but are nevertheless connected to a narrowly circumscribed piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, the one who has such a territory is in advantage over another who lives in a cropless, waterless or oil-free area.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a brief insertion.
Those who say territory, those who say government, those who say politics, also say leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, that is, the need for someone who knows how to regulate things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation over the existing leaderships, especially those of the economy, which have turned out to be insufficient and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and, in a certain sense, even more disturbing aspect: a loss of confidence, an intolerance, an image of inexplicability, a sense of distance, all directed towards a whole class of managers of Western countries.
It seems to be the conviction among large parts of the population that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content is presented to the majority as becoming more and more alien and more traditional.
The demand for leadership thus feeds underground a branched but powerful movement of the disenfranchisement of the leading class and the traditional political establishment. This manifests itself in unforeseen "revolts" of voters and in the sudden change of the collective state of mind of recent times: beginning with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, through the collapse of the Labour Party in Great Britain, towards the rebellion of the American MPs against Bush (and perhaps also the victory of the right in Italy plays a role here).
One gets the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say their format, more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value for what is happening today in the lower social strata of the West and is being further intensified by the financial crisis and driven to over-dimensionality.
In view of all this, it would simply be exaggerated to speak of a "rebellion of the masses".
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
