The scientists have been inspired by the feet of the geckos, which are covered by microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect hold.
The tests carried out with various materials such as glass Teflon and sandpaper have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the holding capacity of the feet of the reptiles and at the same time "can be removed from the wall without problems", says Liming Dai, a researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at Dayton University.
"This material could be used as a transitory adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
For example, to walk up walls like Spiderman? Perhaps so, but the researchers think of a less fascinating benefit, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other areas of application could fall within the field of space.
So for now, the superheroes have to wait.
