Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed because of their refreshing quality and vitamin richness especially in the summer, can cause serious health damage if they are taken at the same time with certain vital medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, Professor of the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points out the risk of both packaged and fresh fruit juices in connection with drug intake. At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he once again sounded the alarm: A glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is enough to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital drugs to the extent that they are virtually eliminated and thus endanger patients' health.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected of being responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs, such as antibiotics, antiasthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, to toxic levels.
MEDICAMENTS IN DRIVER – The same agency of the medicine had warned doctors and patients about the dangers of this mix in a report two years ago, stressing that attention should be paid to what is drunk in combination with drugs such as diazepane or metadon.
IT IS NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT – According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of active substances inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Hence the appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the Università Statale di Milano: "These results are usually forwarded immediately to the various international manufacturers who are so free to change consumer information.
It is therefore advisable to read the package leaflet at all times and, if there are still uncertainties, not to ask a pharmacist or doctor about any shyness", the expert of the Ansa agency emphasizes.
